The '''Conférence Molé''' was a French debating society founded in 1832. 
In 1876 it became the '''Conférence Molé-Tocqueville'''. 
Its purpose was to debate legislation, administration, political economy and general politics.
The debates were modeled on parliamentary procedures and served to train future politicians.
The society also provided a venue where young men of the élite could meet and become known by established political figures. 
The society became dormant in the 1970s but was revived in the 1990s.

==Foundation==

The Conférence Molé was founded during the [[July Monarchy]] on 19 March 1832.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=233}}
It was founded  by the [[Marthe Camille Bachasson, Count of Montalivet|Count of Montalivet]] and sponsored by king [[Louis Philippe]].{{sfn|Mayeur|Corbin|Schweitz|1995|p=47}}
The choice of name has not been explained, but seems to be a reference to the politician [[Louis-Mathieu Molé]] (1781–1855).{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=234}}
One of the co-founders was M. Pontmartin, possibly Armand Pontmartin.
Another was Huard-Delamarre, an advocate.
There were three magistrates: Adrien Gastambide, Gustave Aignan and Édouard Ternaux, nephew of the cashmere manufacturer [[William-Louis Ternaux]].{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=233}}
Four founders were members of the council of state: Mortimer Ternaux, Achille Guilhem, [[Prosper Hochet]] and [[Édouard Bocher]].
Charles His and the Count of Cambis were embassy secretaries, and Grille de Beuzelin was a functionary in a ministry.
Other founders were Edmond Anthoine, Édouard Goupil, Francisque Lefèvre and Alp. d'Herbelot.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=234}}

==Structure==
{{multiple image | width=180|direction=vertical | footer =Noted members
  |image1=Les Hommes N 36 Jules Ferry.jpg |caption1=[[Jules Ferry]]
  |image2=Les Hommes N 25 Jules Grévy.jpg |caption2=[[Jules Grévy]]
  |image3=Les Hommes N 30 Georges Clemenceau.jpg|caption3=[[Georges Clemenceau]]
}}
The headquarters of the Conférence Molé were at 8, rue de Poitiers, in the [[Académie Nationale de Médecine|Academy of Medicine]].
At first the membership was limited to 80, divided into four committees.
Later this was changed to 150, without mention of committees.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=234}}
A list of members seeking admission was prepared each year.
Each candidate had to be sponsored by three members, with a declaration prepared by one of the sponsors.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=234}}
Admission was accepted at the meeting of the members.
The entrance fee was 10 francs, with a contribution of 24 francs for each session, or 48 francs for the year.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=235}}
After ten years of attendance members became honorary members.
The Molé was a place where young men of the élite could mix with notable older men.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=131}}
The board of directors was a permanent body, unlike the presidency which lasted only to six months and was meant to alternate between left and right wing presidents.{{sfn|Béguec|Manigand|2004|p=28}}

The society trained young people in debates and in the workings of a legislative chamber.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=132}}
Its purpose was to study and consider legislation, administration, political economy and general politics.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=235}}
Members met weekly for six months of the year.
The proceedings were modelled on those of the [[Chamber of Deputies (France)|Chamber of Deputies]] or [[Corps législatif]].
A mock bill was tabled by a member, examined in committee and then presented to the general assembly.
After discussion, the members voted on the bill.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=131}}
Topics included prostitution, decentralization and freedom of association.{{sfn|Gerson|2003|p=245}}

It was customary for a member to make their maiden speech on the first occasion after being admitted.{{sfn|An "Attaché"|1885|p=190}}
The members formed factions based on political affinities, like the political groups in parliament.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=131}}
The meeting room contained "desks as in the Chamber, a committee, a gallery.{{sfn|Gerson|2003|p=245}}
Franck Chauveau, president of the society in 1876, said "We naturally acquire a taste here for free institutions, a spirit of discussion and free scrutiny, the habits of parliamentary life of which the Conférence is the image.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=132}}

==History==

The Conférence Molé was an important training group for future political leaders in the July Monarchy.{{sfn|Gerson|2003|p=245}}
Around 1845 the Molé absorbed a similar, well-known society, the Conférence d'Orsay.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=239}}
The Conférence d'Orsay had been founded in 1839 by some young, conservative aristocrats and law students who met at the [[Quai d'Orsay]].
It was joined by [[Louis Ferdinand Alfred Maury]] in 1841 after he left the Conférence Bailly.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=240}}
The Molé played a key role during the [[French Second Republic]].{{sfn|Manigand|2000|p=34}}
In 1850 the Conférence Molé moved to 40, rue des Saints-Pères, following the Academy of Medicine.
It remained there until 7 July 1939.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=239}}

The Molé tended to be moderately conservative under the July Monarchy, and was critical of the authoritarian regime of the [[Second French Empire]].{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=132}}
It was one of the rare places where some degree of free public discussion was allowed under the Empire.{{sfn|Mayeur|Corbin|Schweitz|1995|p=88}}
[[Léon Gambetta]] was admitted to the Molé in 1861 and wrote to his father, "It is no mere lawyers club, but a veritable political assembly with a left, a right, a center; legislative proposals are the sole subject of discussion. It is there that are formed all the political men of France; it is a veritable training ground for the tribune."{{sfn|Nord|1995|p=123}}
Gambetta, like many other French orators, learned the art of public speaking at the Molé.
At that time the Molé met in the [[Café Procope]] in the Rue de l'Ancienne-Comédie, the oldest coffee house in Paris.
Other active members during this period included [[Ernest Picard]], Clément Laurier and Léon Renault.{{sfn|Fraser's Magazine|1881|p=348}}

Debating societies flourished in the second half of the 19th century in the absence of political parties.
Of these, the Conférence Molé, known simply as "Le Molé", was the most influential and the most politicized.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=131}}
Under the [[French Third Republic]] many members of the Molé became parliamentary leaders, so membership was sought after by aspiring politicians.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=132}}
On 28 April 1876 the Conférence Molé merged with the Conférence Tocqueville, which had been founded in 1863.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=239}}
{{efn|The Tocqueville was founded by Charles Savary, a future minister of the Third Republic, for young men who found it too difficult to join the Molé. 
In 1870 it absorbed the less political Conférence La Bruyère, and in 1871 absorbed the Conférence Montesquieu.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=132}} }}
The Conférence Molé-Tocqueville continued to prosper.
By 1886 it had 344 members and 376 former members.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=132}}
The society was less active in the 1880s, but experienced a revival in the 1890s when it was stimulated by competition and the introduction of new debating techniques.{{sfn|Manigand|2000|p=34}}
On 30 April 1897 [[Félix Faure]], President of France, decreed that the Conférence Molé-Tocqueville was an "establishment of public utility".{{sfn|Histoire: La Conférence}}

Of the 320 cabinet members from 1871 to 1914, 26 had belonged to the Molé, 6 to the Tocqueville, 10 to the Molé-Tocqueville and 2 to the Bruyère.
43 ministers, or 13.4%, had belonged to one of these societies.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=132}}
Of Paris municipal councilors between 1871 and 1914, 12 had been members of the Molé, 4 of the Tocqueville and 40 of the Molé-Tocqueville.
[[Édouard Hervé]] had belonged to both the Molé and the Tocqueville before their merger.
A total of 44 people had thus belonged to one of the societies, or 9.7% of the councilors.
These men often played a leading role in the municipal council: 20 were presidents, vice-presidents or secretaries of the council.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=133}}

In the period between [[World War I]] and [[World War II]], 105 deputies belonged to the Conférence Molé-Tocqueville before being elected.{{sfn|Nagai|2002|p=132}}
After World War II the Conférence Molé-Tocqueville resumed its sessions, and had lively debates during the [[Algerian War]].
It became moribund in the 1970s.
A 1989 paper dated the last traces of its existence to 1978.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=239}}
The conference was revived in the 1990s to discuss involvement of civil society in the French economic and social fabric.{{sfn|Histoire: La Conférence}}

==Noted members==

Early members included [[Louis Wolowski]] and Édouard Allou, who became president.{{sfn|Mayeur|Corbin|Schweitz|1995|p=47}}
Several non-removable Senators belonged to the conferences.
Lawyers included [[René Bérenger]], [[Louis Buffet]], Marc Antoine Calmon, [[Jules Cazot]], [[Jean Clamageran]] (president in 1858), Henry Didier, [[Albert Grévy]], [[Édouard René de Laboulaye]] and [[Ernest Picard]] (president in 1853).{{sfn|Mayeur|Corbin|Schweitz|1995|p=87}}
Other noted members included [[Philippe Paul, comte de Ségur|Philippe Paul de Ségur]] (1780–1873), [[James Mayer de Rothschild]] (1792–1868), [[Napoleon III]] (1808–73), [[Jules Ferry]] (1832–93), [[Georges Clemenceau]] (1841–1929), [[Pierre de Coubertin]] (1863–1937), [[André Citroën]] (1878–1935), [[Pierre Taittinger]] (1887–1965) and [[Guy Mollet]] (1905–75).{{sfn|Histoire: La Conférence}}

In 1846 there were 221 members. 
44 had left the society, so a total of 265 had been or were part of it.
Of 230 who gave their professions, 138 were advocates or magistrates, 30 in the Council of State, 16 in public office and 11 diplomats.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=236}}
Of the 265 members up to 1846, 59 became deputies.
30 served under one regime, 18 under two regimes and 9 under 3 regimes.
Werner de Merode and Charles-Pierre-Paul Paulmier were deputies under four regimes: the July Monarchy, French Second Republic, Second French Empire and French Third Republic.
Eight became ministers: [[Louis Buffet]], [[Charles de Morny, Duke of Morny|Charles de Morny]], [[Lionel de Moustier]], Auguste de Talhouët-Royt and [[Adolphe Vuitry]] under the Second Empire, [[Louis, duc Decazes|Louis Decazes]], Eugène de Goulard and [[Pierre Edmond Teisserenc de Bort]] under the Third Republic.
[[Jules Grévy]] was elected president of the Republic in 1879.{{sfn|Martin-Frugier|1989|p=237}}

